sec.p:
To investigate cognition overall, a factor analysis score was used to combine the results of the five cognitive tests (Supplementary Note

 2

). Factor loadings from the baseline were applied to both the baseline and study-end cognitive test results to ensure uniform loadings. One factor was identified from the scree plot as accounting for maximum variance. Thus, a factor score at baseline and study endpoint was derived and subsequently used in the mixed effects models. Linear mixed-effects models were used to compare intervention groups (arm 1 vs arm 2; blinded) on their change in each outcome by using the measure of that outcome at the study end and including the baseline measure in the model. Twin clustering was considered as random effect, both family identifier and zygosity, and treatment group a fixed effect. Two-sided paired t-tests were used for within-group comparisons between baseline and end of intervention.
